**Abstract:**
Working notes dated August 4, 1993, exploring the difference between spoken and written language in relation to biblical interpretation. The document argues that language incarnates communicative intentions between exposed agents, not between invulnerable contemplators, and that the reduction of language to descriptive and explanatory statements reflects a speculative rather than practical theory of language. It examines how contemporaneousness of speaker and hearer in spoken language differs fundamentally from written texts.

**AI Recommendation:** Important notes on philosophy of language; develops distinction between practical and speculative theories of communication.

